<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">CITIGROUP CUTS THIRD-QUARTER PROFIT  <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Citigroup canât seem to catch a break. On Thursday, the bank startled investors with an announcement that it had to lower its third-quarter profit by $600 million because of ârapidly evolving regulatory inquiries and investigations,â <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/30/citigroup-restates-third-quarter-earnings">DealBookâs Michael Corkery, Peter Eavis and Ben Protess write</a></b>. Citigroup reported its results for the quarter two weeks ago, just before the legal development arose. Although the bank did not specify the development, people briefed on the matter attributed the nearly 18 percent drop in earnings to an investigation into whether Citigroup manipulated the price of foreign currencies. Since reporting its third-quarter results, the bank has edged nearer a settlement with at least one regulator in the case, the people said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The $600 million disclosure &#8220;<b>opens a new window into the status of the currency investigation</b>, which has ensnared more than a dozen giant banks,â DealBook writes. Six of those banks, including Citigroup, are near a settlement with British regulators and hope to reach a deal by the end of November, another person briefed on the matter said. Regulators and prosecutors in Washington are expected to take their own actions against the banks.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Also on Thursday, Barclays of Britain said that its third-quarter earnings fell 26 percent, partly because of legal costs related to investigations into its currency markets business. The two announcements underscore the <b>uncertainty surrounding bank results</b>, which can suddenly shift as the size of legal penalties become clearer.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The currency investigation is hardly the only regulatory headache facing Michael L. Corbat, Citigroupâs chief executive. The bank also faces <b>investigations into a $400 million fraud in its Mexican unit</b> involving the oil services company OceanografÃ­a. In a regulatory filing on Thursday, Citigroup said that the Mexican National Banking and Securities Commission had finished its review of the fraud and issued âa corrective actionâ that the bank must put into effect and imposed a $2.2 million fine as well. <b>Shares of Citigroup fell 1.9 percent</b> in after-hours trading on Thursday. The bank announced the adjustment after the stock market had closed.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">APPLE CHIEFâS COMING OUT <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Timothy D. Cook, Appleâs chief executive, said on Thursday that he was gay, becoming the most prominent executive of a public company to openly acknowledge his homosexuality. âLet me be clear: <b>Iâm proud to be gay</b>, and I consider being gay among the greatest gifts God has given me,â Mr. Cook wrote in an essay, published by <b><a href="//www.businessweek.com/articles/2014-10-30/tim-cook-im-proud-to-be-gay">Bloomberg Businessweek</a></b>. Mr. Cookâs decision is the most striking example of how he is in many ways making Apple a more open, less secretive company, <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/31/technology/timothy-cook-apples-chief-executive-says-he-is-proud-to-be-gay.html">Brian X. Chen and Vindu Goel write in The New York Times</a></b>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Business analysts and professors said that Mr. Cookâs decision is <b>unlikely to have any major impact on Appleâs global business</b>. But they added that because it was a bold move, it was full of unknowns. Gay rights advocates, for instance, are still struggling to secure basic protections in Asia, where Apple generated 27 percent of its revenue in its fourth quarter. Still, it seemed unlikely that consumer interest in Apple products or its business partnerships in Asia would be damaged. At home, Mr. Cookâs decision to be public about his sexual orientation stands in remarkable contrast to the culture of secrecy fostered by his predecessor, Steven P. Jobs, who was notoriously guarded.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âGiven widespread rumors that he was gay, including being ranked No. 1 on Out magazineâs list of the most powerful gay people last year, the fact that Mr. Cook is gay is less surprising than his willingness to publicly acknowledge and embrace it,â <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/31/technology/apple-chief-tim-cooks-coming-out-this-will-resonate.html?ref=technology">James B. Stewart writes in the Common Sense column</a></b>. A number of current and former executives, along with gay workers at technology companies, <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/31/technology/tim-cooks-disclosure-that-hes-gay-garners-sweeping-praise.html">praised Mr. Cookâs decision</a></b>. Mr. Cookâs announcement is âhistoric and itâs wonderful,â said Allan Gilmour, who was chief financial officer and a board member at Ford and is gay. As Lloyd Blankfein, the chief executive of Goldman Sachs, put it, âSomething has consequences because of who does it, and this is Tim Cook and Apple. <b>This will resonate powerfully</b>.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Another notable aspect of Mr. Cookâs announcement</b> was where he chose to make it. Rather than write a corporate blog post or sit down for a television interview, Mr. Cook took a low-key approach , <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/31/business/media/coming-out-in-businessweek-tim-cook-chooses-to-play-it-low-key.html">Noam Cohen writes in The New York Times</a></b>. Under a headline that did not directly address the issue â âTim Cook Speaks Upâ â Mr. Cook wrote a sober, conscientious essay for Bloomberg Businessweek. The essay was the latest indication that the magazine and Mr. Cook have forged what appears to be a close relationship. In September, Mr. Cook was on Bloomberg Businessweekâs cover for an article about how he was putting his own stamp on Apple. The magazine also ran a cover piece on Mr. Cook and Apple last year.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">JUDGE APPROVES STOCKTONâS BANKRUPTCY PLAN <span class="divider"> | </span></span> In a closely watched case, a judge on Thursday confirmed a plan by Stockton, Calif., to exit bankruptcy, rejecting arguments that it unfairly discriminated among creditors by cutting a mutual fundâs recovery to near zero while shielding city retirees from any impairment at all, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/30/judge-approves-bankruptcy-exit-for-stockton-calif/">Mary Williams Walsh reports in DealBook</a></b>. Stockton had asked the court to approve its plan, which calls for budget cuts, haircuts for bondholders and a sales tax increase, which city residents approved in a referendum last year. But <b>the plan did not touch pensions</b>, not even the benefits that current workers hope to earn in future years. Prospective pension cuts are routine when companies go bankrupt under Chapter 11 and even outside of bankruptcy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Judge Christopher Klein of the United States Bankruptcy Court for the Eastern District of California in Sacramento said he found Stocktonâs proposed plan acceptable, noting that it <b>eliminated the retireesâ health benefits</b>. He added that rejecting the exit plan would mean running up millions more dollars in legal bills for an alternative exit plan that would probably not be worth the additional cost. Judge Klein cited the âsignificant concessionsâ that Stocktonâs employees and retirees had made, especially the cancellation of the retiree health plan, which he said amounted to a $550 million loss. He also noted that the city workersâ pay was being reduced, which would lead to smaller pensions because the benefits are linked to each workerâs salary before retirement.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Judge Klein said he had not changed his thinking about pensions since his previous decision on the issue, made from the bench earlier this month. He said at that point that Stockton was <b>free to abrogate its contract with  Californiaâs state pension system, Calpers, in bankruptcy</b> and that Calpers would be a mere unsecured creditor with no special legal tools to improve its chance of recovery. On Thursday, Judge Klein reiterated that federal bankruptcy law pre-empted the state law giving Calpers a lien that allowed it to claim $1.6 billion worth of Stocktonâs assets if the city stopped making payments and dropped out of the state pension system. Without the lien, the relationship between Calpers and Stockton became contractual, he said. That part of Judge Kleinâs decision left the door open for other California cities to end their relationships with Calpers, at relatively low cost, by declaring bankruptcy.</p>
</div>
